\title{Mcp From Prompt}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{version}{1.0.0}

\meta{description}{Generate a complete MCP server + skill from an API description, following the ExoPriors Scry prompt pattern. Use when building a new MCP server for any REST API or data source.}

\subtree{
\title{MCP-from-Prompt}
\p{Generate a production-ready MCP server + Claude skill from an API description. Follows the ExoPriors Scry pattern — the most effective prompt format for agent-API interaction.}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use}
\ul{
\li{User wants to wrap a REST API as an MCP server}
\li{User has an API they want Claude to use via tools}
\li{User says "make an MCP for X" or "create a skill for Y API"}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Prompt Sources}
\p{The API description / prompt can come from:}

\subtree{
\title{Local file}
\pre{\startverb
/mcp-from-prompt ~/docs/my-api-spec.md
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{LAN URL (http://, any port)}
\pre{\startverb
/mcp-from-prompt http://10.1.10.107:8080/prompt.md
/mcp-from-prompt http://conversation-logger:5000/api/spec
/mcp-from-prompt http://192.168.1.50:3000/openapi.json
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Tailscale URL}
\pre{\startverb
/mcp-from-prompt http://thoughtspace:8080/prompt.md
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Fetch procedure}
\p{When the argument looks like a URL (\code{\startverb http://\stopverb} or \code{\startverb https://\stopverb}):}

\ol{
\li{Use \code{\startverb curl -sS --connect-timeout 5\stopverb} (LAN URLs) or WebFetch (public URLs)}
\li{If JSON, treat as OpenAPI spec}
\li{If markdown/text, treat as free-form API description}
\li{Parse into the effective format below}
}

\p{This means you can run a simple HTTP server on any LAN machine:}

\pre{\startverb
# On the remote machine:
cd /path/to/prompts && python -m http.server 8080
# Then from Claude Code:
/mcp-from-prompt http://that-machine:8080/my-api.md
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{The Effective Format (4 files)}
\p{Every generated skill produces exactly 4 files:}

\subtree{
\title{1. \code{\startverb SKILL.md\stopverb} — The Skill Registration}
\p{This makes it a proper \code{\startverb /skill-name\stopverb} command in Claude Code.}

\pre{\startverb
---
name: {kebab-name}
description: {One sentence: what this skill does and when to trigger it.}
version: 1.0.0
---

# {Service Name}

{2-3 sentence summary of what the MCP tools do and what data they access.}

## Tools Available

- `{service}_{verb1}` — {what it does}
- `{service}_{verb2}` — {what it does}

## Quick Patterns

### {Most common use case}
1. Call `{service}_{verb1}` with `{param}`
2. Use result to call `{service}_{verb2}`

### {Second use case}
1. ...

## Reference

See [instructions.md](instructions.md) for full schema, API reference, and gotchas.
\stopverb}

\subtree{
\title{SKILL.md Rules}
\ul{
\li{Under 80 lines — this loads into every conversation where the skill triggers}
\li{Link to \code{\startverb instructions.md\stopverb} for details — agent reads it on demand}
\li{List tools by name so the agent knows what's available without loading the MCP}
\li{\startverb Quick Patterns = the 2-3 things the user will ask for 90% of the time\stopverb}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. \code{\startverb instructions.md\stopverb} — The Agent Prompt}
\p{This is the prompt engineering core. Structure EXACTLY as follows:}

\pre{\startverb
# {Service Name} — {One-Liner Purpose}

{Single sentence: what + scale + sources.}

## API Quick Reference

| Method | Endpoint | Content-Type | Body |
|--------|----------|--------------|------|
| POST | `/v1/...` | `text/plain` | Raw payload |
| POST | `/v1/...` | `application/json` | `{"field":"..."}` |
| GET  | `/v1/...` | — | — |

**Base URL**: `https://api.example.com`
**Auth**: `Authorization: Bearer {token_name}`

### Limits
- {Concrete limit 1}
- {Concrete limit 2}

## Core Schema

### {primary_table}
| Column | Type | Notes |
|--------|------|-------|
| id | UUID | PK |
| ... | ... | {Essential context only} |

### {secondary_table}
| Column | Type | Notes |
|--------|------|-------|

### Pre-indexed Views (fast paths)
- **{category}**: `view_a`, `view_b`, `view_c`
- **{category}**: `view_d`, `view_e`

## Key Operations

### Pattern: {most common operation}
\stopverb}

\p{{Concrete, copy-pasteable example}}

\pre{\startverb

### Pattern: {second most common}
\stopverb}

\p{{Concrete example}}

\pre{\startverb

### Pattern: {advanced composition}
\stopverb}

\p{{Example combining multiple operations}}

\pre{\startverb

## Gotchas

1. **{Short name}**: {One sentence explaining the trap + fix.}
2. **{Short name}**: {One sentence.}
3. ...
\stopverb}

\subtree{
\title{Why This Format Works}
\pre{\startverb
| Element | Purpose |
|---------|---------|
| **Table-driven API ref** | Agent parses tables faster than prose |
| **Schema with Notes column** | Encodes domain knowledge inline, not separate docs |
| **Pre-indexed views** | Safe starting points — agent picks these first |
| **Pattern sections** | Copy-paste templates beat abstract descriptions |
| **Gotchas (numbered)** | Prevents known failure modes before they happen |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Anti-patterns to Avoid}
\ul{
\li{No tutorials or explanations of concepts}
\li{No "Overview" or "Introduction" sections}
\li{No installation instructions}
\li{No version history}
\li{No links to external docs (they can't follow them)}
\li{Never describe what a tool "could" do — show what it DOES}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. \code{\startverb {name}_mcp.py\stopverb} — The MCP Server}
\p{Structure:}

\pre{\startverb
"""
{Service} MCP Server — stdio transport.

Wraps the {Service} API as {N} MCP tools:
  {tool_1}, {tool_2}, ...

Run:  python {name}_mcp.py
"""

from __future__ import annotations
import json, ssl, sys, os
from typing import Any
import httpx
from mcp.server import Server
from mcp.server.stdio import stdio_server
from mcp.types import TextContent, Tool

# --- Constants ---
BASE_URL = os.environ.get("{NAME}_BASE_URL", "https://api.example.com")
API_KEY = os.environ.get("{NAME}_API_KEY", "")
AUTH_HEADER = {"Authorization": f"Bearer {API_KEY}"} if API_KEY else {}
TIMEOUT = httpx.Timeout(60.0, connect=10.0)

# --- SSL (Cloudflare compat) ---
def _make_ssl_context() -> ssl.SSLContext:
    ctx = ssl.create_default_context()
    ctx.minimum_version = ssl.TLSVersion.TLSv1_2
    return ctx

# --- HTTP client ---
def _build_client() -> httpx.AsyncClient:
    proxy = os.environ.get("{NAME}_SOCKS_PROXY")
    return httpx.AsyncClient(
        base_url=BASE_URL,
        headers=AUTH_HEADER,
        timeout=TIMEOUT,
        http2=True,
        verify=_make_ssl_context(),
        **({"proxy": proxy} if proxy else {}),
    )

async def _request(
    method: str, path: str, *,
    content: str | None = None,
    json_body: dict[str, Any] | None = None,
    content_type: str | None = None,
) -> dict[str, Any]:
    headers: dict[str, str] = {}
    if content_type:
        headers["Content-Type"] = content_type
    async with _build_client() as client:
        resp = await client.request(
            method, path,
            content=content.encode() if content else None,
            json=json_body, headers=headers,
        )
        resp.raise_for_status()
        return resp.json()

# --- MCP server ---
server = Server("{name}")

@server.list_tools()
async def list_tools() -> list[Tool]:
    return [
        # One Tool() per API endpoint
        # inputSchema: only required fields + most-used optional
        # description: action verb, what it returns
    ]

@server.call_tool()
async def call_tool(name: str, arguments: dict[str, Any]) -> list[TextContent]:
    try:
        # Route to endpoint, return JSON
        ...
    except httpx.HTTPStatusError as exc:
        return [TextContent(type="text", text=f"HTTP {exc.response.status_code}: {exc.response.text}")]
    except Exception as exc:
        return [TextContent(type="text", text=f"Error: {exc}")]

async def main() -> None:
    async with stdio_server() as (read_stream, write_stream):
        await server.run(read_stream, write_stream, server.create_initialization_options())

if __name__ == "__main__":
    import asyncio
    asyncio.run(main())
\stopverb}

\subtree{
\title{MCP Server Rules}
\ul{
\li{\strong{1 tool per API endpoint} — no combined tools}
\li{\strong{Tool names}: \code{\startverb {service}_{verb}\stopverb} (e.g., \code{\startverb scry_query\stopverb}, \code{\startverb scry_embed\stopverb})}
\li{\strong{Descriptions}: Start with action verb, say what format returns}
\li{\strong{inputSchema}: Only \code{\startverb required\stopverb} fields + top 2-3 optional. Use \code{\startverb description\stopverb} on every field}
\li{\strong{Strip large payloads}: Filter vectors/blobs from results by default, add \code{\startverb include_X\stopverb} flag}
\li{\strong{Env vars for config}: \code{\startverb {NAME}_BASE_URL\stopverb}, \code{\startverb {NAME}_API_KEY\stopverb}, \code{\startverb {NAME}_SOCKS_PROXY\stopverb}}
\li{\strong{SSL context}: Always include for Cloudflare compat}
\li{\strong{httpx + h2}: Async, HTTP/2, 60s timeout}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{4. \code{\startverb run.sh\stopverb} — The Shell Wrapper}
\pre{\startverb
#!/bin/sh
unset PYTHONPATH
export {NAME}_API_KEY="$(/Users/alice/.cargo/bin/fnox get {KEY_NAME} --age-key-file /Users/alice/.age/key.txt -c /Users/alice/v/instance-onboarding/fnox.toml)"
exec uvx --from 'mcp[cli]' --with httpx --with h2 python /Users/alice/.claude/skills/{skill-name}/{name}_mcp.py
\stopverb}

\p{If SOCKS proxy needed, add:}

\pre{\startverb
export {NAME}_SOCKS_PROXY="socks5h://localhost:19050"
\stopverb}

\p{and add \code{\startverb --with 'httpx[socks]'\stopverb} to the uvx line.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Generation Workflow}
\p{When asked to create an MCP for a service:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Fetch} — Get the prompt/spec from wherever it lives:}
\li{\strong{LAN URL}: \code{\startverb curl -sS --connect-timeout 5 'http://10.1.10.107:8080/prompt.md'\stopverb}}
\li{\strong{Tailscale URL}: \code{\startverb curl -sS --connect-timeout 5 'http://thoughtspace:8080/spec.json'\stopverb}}
\li{\strong{Public URL}: Use WebFetch}
\li{\strong{Local file}: Read directly}
\li{\strong{User-provided text}: Use as-is}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Distill} — Reduce to the effective format:}
\li{API table: only endpoints the agent will actually use}
\li{Schema: only columns that matter for queries}
\li{Patterns: 3-5 concrete, copy-paste examples}
\li{Gotchas: things that WILL trip up the agent}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Generate} — Write all 4 files to \code{\startverb /Users/alice/.claude/skills/{name}/\stopverb}:}
\li{\code{\startverb SKILL.md\stopverb} (skill registration, <80 lines)}
\li{\code{\startverb instructions.md\stopverb} (full agent prompt)}
\li{\code{\startverb {name}_mcp.py\stopverb} (MCP server)}
\li{\code{\startverb run.sh\stopverb} (shell wrapper)}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Register} — Run:}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Test} — Call each tool once to verify connectivity}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Key Insight}
\p{The instructions.md IS the prompt. It is loaded into Claude's context when the skill activates. Every line costs tokens. The format above is optimized for:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Parseability}: Tables > prose for structured data}
\li{\strong{Actionability}: Patterns > descriptions for "what do I do"}
\li{\strong{Error prevention}: Gotchas > debugging for known failure modes}
\li{\strong{Token efficiency}: No fluff, no tutorials, no history}
}
}
}